@granders Turns out the seemingly innocuous change to `SecurityConfig` actually changed the output a bit by removing a leading `\n`, which meant two configs ended up on the same line and broke some config files if they didn't have the necessary newline before concatenating. While we really should just insert the security config via templating, since we seem to already be manually stringifying and concatenating in a bunch of tests I simply added the newline characters back in and have validated locally that the Connect security tests continue to pass and a MM test with security enabled also passes.

I also reduced the test to only do `PLAINTEXT` and `SASL_SSL` as @ijuma suggested. I think it's better to avoid a ton of extra variants here since we don't expect any difference between the different modes, we just care that the options are actually passed properly to producers/consumers.

I kicked off a new test build here: https://jenkins.confluent.io/job/system-test-kafka-branch-builder/404/

@granthenke I was thinking of doing it without exposing the config. e.g.:

`protected[auth] def maxUpdateRetries = ...`

Then, we can override the method in the test (a constructor param could also be used, but it would require a secondary no-args constructor and I prefer to avoid those in Scala).

@granthenke If the operation fails after max retries, users are free to back-off and try again, right?. It's a good enough workaround for the uncommon case. This is why max retries was suggested IMO, we want to let users decide instead of continuously retrying.

We could change the test to do something similar if we want, but the test is a stress test and so it seemed like continuously retrying would be OK for the test.

Adding a config is not a simple thing, unfortunately. It has serious downsides. Each config we add, we make it harder for users to correctly configure the system. Kafka suffers from this problem today even though there is a concerted effort not to add new configs (imagine how bad it would be if there wasn't).

@guozhangwang I haven't seen that before. The tests passed locally. This failure appeared in very old JIRAs:

https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/KAFKA-427
https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/KAFKA-435

@granders, ready for another round of reviews. I addressed your feedback and added version support to `benchmark_test.py`. I don't have any other changes planned.

I tested the relevant tests via the AWS test driver and things seem fine. I also started a full system tests run via the branch builder:

https://jenkins.confluent.io/job/system-test-kafka-branch-builder/407/
